›››              Comprehensive Case #1›››     This is a case about a young lady and her financial situation. The young lady I am speaking of is Kendra Winston. Kendra has just recently graduated from college with a degree in business. Her interests are in finance and marketing. She has also just landed a job at a real-estate firm known as Franson and Associates. Kendra's employer offers a wide variety of financial benefits to its employees in which she has an obligation to partake in which would benefit her financial future. However, Kendra does not believe that a single person her age needs to incorporate the use of a formal budget. She believes that she has plenty of money that she has saved over the years and also earns enough to buy many of the things that she desired when she was growing up. Therefore in this paper I would like to discuss some issues of Kendra and her budget.››     Some of the issues that come to mind about Kendra's financial situation are quite obvious. For instance, how does her current personal situation influence her financial planning and decision making? Next is, what might be some of her financial goals in the future? Next, what are some of the factors she should consider in constructing a savings and/or investment program and how would a budget help? Yet another thing to consider is how should Kendra take advantage of her company's supplementary benefits such as training opportunities and pension plan, and how might these influence her if her life takes on additional changes? Also, what kind of tax planning should she be looking into, based on her current lifestyle? And last but not least, what other type of financial considerations should she take into account at this point in her life?››     To begin let's answer the first question. Since Kendra is young, single, and making good money, she thinks that she can go ahead and spend frivolously. When she was a child and growing up she always had to wear hand-me-downs and never really had anything to call her own. This just adds fuel to the fire if you will. What she needs to do is step back and take a look at her actions. She needs to accept the value of her hard earned money and not just spend at will. ›     As for future financial goals, this is a wide open area. There are many avenues Kendra can take and they all rely on her needs and plans. But to add some influence to her she may want to think about marriage and a family, perhaps she may want a new car or own a home, she may want to travel or take on a new hobby. In what ever she decides, she will need to have money, and in order to have money she needs to come up with some new and improved ways to save and earn more money to facilitate her choices.›     There are many ways to go about building a savings and investment program. Some very simple ways according to my personal finance book is to put a specific dollar amount or maybe 5 to 10 percent of your paycheck into a savings account. Some employers even take out an agreed amount for you and can send it to a savings account. This technique is known as payroll deduction. There are also many investment options that she can pursue. For example there are savings bonds, stocks, bonds, and mutual funds. Other ways to save is to use common sense. Just plain spending less on unnecessary items could save a lot. She could also come up with a plan to spend only a specific amount of money per month on entertainment or other personal needs and then try to stay at this figure or even try to stay under it.›     In order to take advantage of the training opportunities offered by her company she should first ask herself, "Do I have the desire for success and financial advancement which I can obtain through increased education?" If her answer is 'YES', then by all means she should take advantage of training opportunities. There are no ways that this could hurt her, she can only move up. Kendra should take advantage of every supplemental employee benefit that she can. But she needs to look at which ones will benefit her the most, especially in the long run. SHe should take the extra health and life insurance benefits. These will help her the most, especially with today's rising medical and health care rates. She can also get the use of a financial planners services. His or her advice to Kendra would best tell her how to manage her money. The other benefits are good to take advantage of too, but if she ever comes across some serious personal problems, her insurance and pension plan will probably benefit her the most. Speaking of pension plans, if Kendra accepts the additional pension plan of $750 a year, after 40 years at 9% interest compounded annually, her account would be worth ($750*(40,9%)=$253,417.50!!›     Now about Kendra's tax planning. She should try to see if she can get any deductions and exemptions. In other words try to reduce her taxable income as much as possible. According to the Wall Street Journal, inflation is low, so as a result exemptions and deductions will rise slightly for the year 1993. It is predicted that the deductions for a single person will go up $100. A single person will also lose his or her exemptions when their adjusted gross income exceeds $108,450 which is up from 1992's threshold of $105,250. There one thing for sure though, everybody pays taxes, but the less one has to pay the better.›     At this point in her life Kendra should be looking into investing for the future. In other words, she puts in a little now and in the future she have earned many times over. Some ways of doing this is buy U.S. Bonds, or buying into a mutual fund. The financial planner provided by her company could probably give her the best information about investments. Perhaps in the future she may want to mortgage a house and/or raise a family, in which case she'll have to refocus her financial goals.››     In summary, no matter who you are or how independent you may think you are, everybody needs to have some sort of financial budget. A budget can help your money management now and in the future. Even Kendra needs a budget. Financial planning is something everyone can benefit from.